{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"28049a9d-6011-444b-bd3b-f914eed64593","content":"The change is straightforward. In your project file, simply remove (or set to `false`) the `UseVSTest` property:\n\n**Before:**\n```xml\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n**After:**\n```xml\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <!-- UseVSTest removed — Microsoft.Testing.Platform is the default -->\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\nMSTest.Sdk 3.8.0 uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform **by default**, so you just need to delete the `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` line.\n\n### Key differences to be aware of:\n\n| Area | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| **Run tests** | `dotnet test` still works; you can also run the test exe directly |\n| **CLI options** | Platform uses `--` syntax (e.g., `--filter` instead of `--testcasefilter`) |\n| **Extensions** | VSTest adapters are replaced by platform extensions (most built-in with MSTest.Sdk) |\n| **`.runsettings`** | Still supported, but platform-native config via code is preferred |\n\nIf you had any VSTest-specific adapters or custom test loggers, you'll need their Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalents.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ac4f19e0-945f-484b-8ed6-afbfff29cf26","outputTokens":357,"requestId":"BD13:319933:1CA5DA2:204E675:6A07C507"},"id":"d1660957-a0ca-44ce-bb35-dc7804a25fbc","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:14:56.093Z","parentId":"cb7b4739-5d09-42e8-ace6-5e11117564a9"}
